<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
[[ Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus Linnaeus</taxonomicName>
]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
The Neotropical electric fish genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus (Linnaeus 1758)</taxonomicName>
is substantially more diverse than was previously recognized. New methods of sampling, identifying, and collecting electric fishes have unveiled numerous species in previously unexplored habitats and regions (Crampton 1996a; Lundberg et al.1996; Crampton 1998; Albert &amp; Crampton 2001). Further, the use of new techniques for characterizing morphology, electric organ discharges, and genetic differences have demonstrated that much of what was once regarded as intraspecific variation represents interspecific differences (Campos-da-Paz &amp; Costa 1996; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 1998a; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 1998b; Albert et al. 1999; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 2000; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 2001; Albert &amp; Crampton 2001; Fernandes-Matioli &amp; Almeida-Toledo, 2001).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="3" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
species are aggressive nocturnal predators of fishes and other small aquatic animals, and most are territorial. The males of at least two 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
species build and guard nests of foam and/or aquatic vegetation (Crampton &amp; Hopkins pers. obs.). The type species 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">Gymnotus carapo</taxonomicName>
is reported to mouth brood its eggs and larvae (Kirschbaum &amp; Wieczorek 2002). 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
is the most geographically widespread of all gymnotiforms, extending from the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Salado in the Pampas of Argentina (36°S) to the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
San 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Nicolás">Nicolas</normalizedToken>
of southeastern Chiapas, Mexico (18°N), and is present in the continental waters of all South and Middle American countries except Chile and Belize (Albert 2001). Prior to this report, 25 species names were available for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
, of which five were synonymized with the type species 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
(Mago-Leccia 1994), and one with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:960361B6-04A3-4620-8652-4250EE5C9E8A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus coatesi La Monte 1935:1" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coatesi">G. coatesi</taxonomicName>
(Campos da Paz 2000). The geographical ranges of the currently valid 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
species are summarized in Table 1. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
exhibits its greatest diversity in the western portion of the Amazon basin where 10 species are currently recognized. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7C0439E9-4610-4E00-9082-E644403A1653" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus anguillaris Hoedeman 1962:55" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anguillaris">Gymnotus anguillaris Hoedeman</taxonomicName>
is recognized here as distinct from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:71F3A25A-999A-43FE-93D9-F3936F1178D5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus coropinae Hoedeman 1962:55" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coropinae">G. coropinae Hoedeman</taxonomicName>
with which it has been synonymized (Nijssen &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Isbrücker">Isbruecker</normalizedToken>
1968). Data for and comparisons to 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:71F3A25A-999A-43FE-93D9-F3936F1178D5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus coropinae Hoedeman 1962:55" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coropinae">G. coropinae</taxonomicName>
will be presented in a forthcoming redescription of this species (Crampton &amp; Albert unpubl. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="4" pageNumber="3">
Here we present evidence for the existence of seven new species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
from examination of populations from throughout tropical South and Middle America. We describe these new taxa on the basis of unique color patterns and unique combinations of morphometric, meristic, and osteological features. We also redescribe the geographically widespread species 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
sensu stricto (
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
s.s.) and distinguish six allopatric populations of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
s.s. by differences in the mean and modal values of morphometric and meristic traits. The original description of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo (Linnaeus, 1758)</taxonomicName>
provides only enough information to identify specimens to the Order Gymnotiformes (sensu MagoLeccia, 1994). Subsequent diagnoses and keys (Ellis 1913; Hoedeman 1962; Mago-Leccia 1994; Albert &amp; Miller 1995) did not provide sufficient information to differentiate 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
s.s. from other member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
species-group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="4">
The material basis of these descriptions is 781 museum lots of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
bearing more than 2700 specimens from 32 museums. This study is to our knowledge the most thorough alpha-level review of morphological variation in any gymnotiform genus to date. The existence of so many previously unrecognized and undescribed taxa within existing museum collections is due in part to the cryptic nature of phenotypic diversity in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
. These fishes possess few external visual cues for species recognition. The lack of appreciation for diversity in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
has been compounded by a lack of published accounts of intraspecific variation. We predict that similarly high levels of cryptic diversity may exist in other gymnotiform groups with geographic distributions well represented in museum collections (e.g., 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:71161FC6-E04D-4A81-A298-4DDB7CB5F7E0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Hypopomidae" genus="Brachyhypopomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Brachyhypopomus Mago-Leccia 1994:47" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Brachyhypopomus</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:872C4DCC-61A5-4BE1-A04B-B4708D60C673" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rhamphichthyidae" genus="Gymnorhamphichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnorhamphichthys Ellis 1912:423, 436" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnorhamphichthys</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sternopygidae" genus="Eigenmannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Eigenmannia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6F85136B-D848-4991-BCE1-D75B760B078E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Sternarchorhynchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sternarchorhynchus Castelnau 1855:91, 95" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sternarchorhynchus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
